  "prompt": "How are passive and active transport different?",
  "response": "Passive and active transport are two types of cellular transport mechanisms that differ in several important ways.\n\nPassive transport is the movement of substances across a cell membrane without the use of energy. This type of transport occurs naturally due to the random movement of molecules and follows the concentration gradient, meaning substances move from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration. There are three main types of passive transport: simple diffusion, facilitated diffusion, and osmosis.\n\nActive transport, on the other hand, is the movement of substances across a cell membrane against the concentration gradient, meaning substances move from an area of lower concentration to an area of higher concentration. This process requires the cell to expend energy, usually in the form of ATP. Active transport is carried out by specific proteins that act as pumps, moving substances across the cell membrane.\n\nIn summary, passive and active transport differ in their use of energy, the direction of movement relative to the concentration gradient, and the mechanisms used to move substances across the cell membrane.",
